1.3 Confidence Interval

Boxplots show how the medians of the two distributions compare, but we can also compare the means of the distributions using either a confidence interval or a hypothesis test.

yrbss %>%
  group_by(physical_3plus) %>%
  filter(!is.na(physical_3plus)) %>% 
  summarise(mean_weight = mean(weight, na.rm = TRUE),
            sd_weight = sd(weight, na.rm=TRUE),
            count = n(),
            se_weight = sd_weight/sqrt(count),
            t_critical = qt(0.975, count-1), 
            margin_of_error = t_critical * se_weight,
            lower = mean_weight - t_critical * se_weight,
            upper = mean_weight + t_critical * se_weight
            )
## # A tibble: 2 x 9
##   physical_3plus mean_weight sd_weight count se_weight t_critical
##   <chr>                <dbl>     <dbl> <int>     <dbl>      <dbl>
## 1 no                    66.7      17.6  4404     0.266       1.96
## 2 yes                   68.4      16.5  8906     0.175       1.96
## # ... with 3 more variables: margin_of_error <dbl>, lower <dbl>, upper <dbl>

There is an observed difference of about 1.77kg (68.44 - 66.67), and we notice that the two confidence intervals do not overlap. It seems that the difference is at least 95% statistically significant. Let us also conduct a hypothesis test.

1.4 Hypothesis test with formula

Write the null and alternative hypotheses for testing whether mean weights are different for those who exercise at least times a week and those who dont.

Null hypotheses: true difference in mean weights for high schoolers who exercise at least 3 times a week and those who dont is equal to 0

Alternative hypotheses: true difference in mean weights is not equal to 0

t.test(weight ~ physical_3plus, data = yrbss)
##

1.5 Hypothesis test with infer

We need to initialize the test, which we will save as obs_diff.

obs_diff <- yrbss %>%
  specify(weight ~ physical_3plus) %>%
  calculate(stat = "diff in means", order = c("yes", "no"))

After we have initialized the test, we need to simulate the test on the null distribution, which we will save as null.

null_dist <- yrbss %>%
  specify(weight ~ physical_3plus) %>%
  hypothesize(null = "independence") %>%
  generate(reps = 1000, type = "permute") %>%
  calculate(stat = "diff in means", order = c("yes", "no"))

We can visualize this null distribution with the following code:

ggplot(data = null_dist, aes(x = stat)) +
  geom_histogram()

Now that the test is initialized and the null distribution formed, we can visualise to see how many of these null permutations have a difference of at least obs_stat of 1.77?

We can also calculate the p-value for your hypothesis test using the function infer::get_p_value().

null_dist %>% visualize() +
  shade_p_value(obs_stat = obs_diff, direction = "two-sided")

null_dist %>%
  get_p_value(obs_stat = obs_diff, direction = "two_sided")
## # A tibble: 1 x 1
##   p_value
##     <dbl>
## 1       0

We run hypothesis tests using both the t.test command and the infer package to simulate from a null distribution, where we assume zero difference between the two.

# Getting p-value using t.test:

t.test(rating~director, data=useful_movies)
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  rating by director
## t = 2, df = 27, p-value = 0.04
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  0.0351 1.0127
## sample estimates:
## mean in group Steven Spielberg       mean in group Tim Burton 
##                           7.57                           7.05
# Getting p-value using infer:

# We randomize
set.seed(5648)

ratings_in_null_world<-useful_movies %>%
  
# Specify the variable of interest
specify(rating~director) %>%
  
# Hypothesize a null of no (or zero) difference
hypothesize(null = "independence") %>%
  
# Generate a bunch of simulated samples
generate(reps=1000 , type ="permute")%>%
  
# Find the mean difference of each sample
calculate(stat = "diff in means",
          order = c("Steven Spielberg", "Tim Burton"))


#visualize how extreme would the observed results be if we simulate a hypothesized population
ratings_in_null_world %>% visualize()+
   shade_p_value(obs_stat =ratings_in_null_world, direction = "both")

#Calculate a p-value
ratings_in_null_world %>%
  get_pvalue(obs_stat= 0.52, direction = "both")
## # A tibble: 1 x 1
##   p_value
##     <dbl>
## 1   0.028

Before anything, we write down the null and alternative hypotheses, as well as the resulting test statistic and the associated t-stat or p-value.

Answer: Critical p-value = 0.05 Null hypothesis: Spielberg mean IMBD rating - Burton mean IMBD rating = 0 ; p-value is equal to or greater than 0.05 Alternative hypothesis: Difference != 0 ; p-vlaue is smaller than 0.05 p-stat using t.test= 0.04 p-stat using simulated null distribution= 0.054

At the end of the day, what do you conclude?

Conclusion We can see that the observed difference of 0.52 is extreme on the simulatio-based null distribution. We can also see that under the 95% confidence interval for the difference, 0.0351 to 1.0127 does not include zero. The infer test and t.test give p-values of 0.028 and 0.04 respectively. There is a 2.8% probabilty that our randomly generated samples from a population with mean difference zero would produce the observed difference. There is a 4% chance of encountering the observed difference if the true difference was zero. Both these p-values are smaller than the 0.05 critical p-value. At the 95% confidence level We can therefore reject the null hypothesis of Spielberg and Burton having same ratings. Given that out observed difference is positive, we can also conclude with 95% confidence that Spielberg has higher ratings than Burton.

3 Omega Group plc- Pay Discrimination

At the last board meeting of Omega Group Plc., the headquarters of a large multinational company, the issue was raised that women were being discriminated in the company, in the sense that the salaries were not the same for male and female executives. A quick analysis of a sample of 50 employees (of which 24 men and 26 women) revealed that the average salary for men was about 8,700 higher than for women. This seemed like a considerable difference, so it was decided that a further analysis of the company salaries was warranted.

salary_stats<- omega %>%

          t_criticial=qt(0.05/2,Sample_Size-1),
          
          Standard_Error=(Standard_Deviation/sqrt(Sample_Size)),
          
          margin_of_error=Standard_Error*t_criticial,
          
          CI_high=mean_salary+margin_of_error,

Conclusion

On average the salary for men and women differs by almost 10k. However, this does not mean that the difference is necessarily significant. To evaluate whether the difference is significant we can look at the confidence intervals:

The confidence Intervals do not overlap. Thus with 95% confidence we can conclude that there is a difference in population means between male and females salaries.

Another way of determining whether the difference in salaries is significant is to test the null hypothesis=

Mean difference in salaries is zero.

We can test this using 1) t.test() and 2) the simulation method from the infer package

  1. hypothesis testing using t.test()
# first we have to check whether the populations have an equal or unequal variance using the Barlett test 

salary_variance <- bartlett.test(salary ~ gender,

  1. Hypothesis testing using infer package
null_distribution <- omega %>% 

# specify response variable and explanatory variable 
  specify(salary~gender) %>% 

# hypothesize H0 (use independence because we have two samples)

  hypothesize(null="independence") %>% 

# generate replicates

  generate(reps=1000, type="permute") %>% 

# calculate summary statistics
  
  calculate(stat = "diff in means", order = c("male","female"))

##   <dbl>
## 1 8696.
  visualize(null_distribution, bins =10)+
  
  shade_p_value(obs_stat =obs_diff_means, direction = "both")

obs_diff_means %>% 
  get_p_value(obs_stat = 8696,direction = "both")
## # A tibble: 1 x 1
##   p_value
##     <dbl>
## 1       0

Conclusion:

Both methods show us that with 95% confidence we can say that there is a statistically significant difference in salaries between men and women.

  • the t.test method shows a p value < 0.05 (the difference in means we observed is highly surprising in a world where h0 holds true) a t value whose absolute value is higher than 2, and the confidence interval does not include 0

  • the infer method shows that the probability of an observed difference in means of about 8697 is very unlikely where H0=there is no difference in means between genders holds true with p value = 0

3.3 Relationship Experience - Gender?

At the board meeting, someone raised the issue that there was indeed a substantial difference between male and female salaries, but that this was attributable to other reasons such as differences in experience. A questionnaire send out to the 50 executives in the sample reveals that the average experience of the men is approximately 21 years, whereas the women only have about 7 years experience on average (see table below).

4 Challenge 1: Yield Curve inversion

Every so often, we hear warnings from commentators on the inverted yield curve and its predictive power with respect to recessions. An explainer what a inverted yield curve is can be found here. If youd rather listen to something, here is a great podcast from NPR on yield curve indicators

In addition, many articles and commentators think that, e.g., Yield curve inversion is viewed as a harbinger of recession. One can always doubt whether inversions are truly a harbinger of recessions, and use the attached parable on yield curve inversions.

In our case we looked at US data and used the FRED database to download historical yield curve rates, and plot the yield curves since 1999 to see when the yield curves flatten. If you want to know more, a very nice article that explains the yield curve is and its inversion can be found here. At the end of this section this graph is reproduced.

First, we use the tidyquant package to download monthly rates for different durations.

# Get a list of FRED codes for US rates and US yield curve; choose monthly frequency
# to see, eg., the 3-month T-bill https://fred.stlouisfed.org/series/TB3MS
tickers <- c('TB3MS', # 3-month Treasury bill (or T-bill)
             'TB6MS', # 6-month

             'GS2',   # 2-year, etc....

According to Wikipedias list of recession in the United States, since 1999 there have been two recession in the US: between Mar 2001Nov 2001 and between Dec 2007June 2009.

The yield curve flattens at both time-points prior to the recession. The yield curve flattening occers when the near term bonds have better yield than longterm bonds, in this case when 3-month offer higher yield than 10-year treasuries.

Can a yield curve flattening really mean a recession is coming in the US? Since 1999, short-term (3 months) yield offered better return than longer term (10 years) debt at three time points, ~2001, ~2008, and again in ~2019.

Besides calculating the spread (10year - 3months), there are a few things we need to do to produce our final plot

  1. Setup data for US recessions
  2. Superimpose recessions as the grey areas in our plot
  3. Plot the spread between 30 years and 3 months as a blue/red ribbon, based on whether the spread is positive (blue) or negative(red)
  • For the first, the code below creates a dataframe with all US recessions since 1946
  • To add the grey shaded areas corresponding to recessions, we use geom_rect()
  • to colour the ribbons blue/red we must see whether the spread is positive or negative and then use geom_ribbon(). You should be familiar with this from last weeks homework on the excess weekly/monthly rentals of Santander Bikes in London.
knitr::include_graphics(here::here("images", "yield_curve_challenge.png"), error = FALSE)

# get US recession dates after 1946 from Wikipedia 
# https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_recessions_in_the_United_States

recessions <- tibble(
  from = c("1960-04-01", "1969-12-01", "1973-11-01", "1980-01-01","1981-07-01", "1990-07-01", "2001-03-01", "2007-12-01"),  
  to = c("1961-02-01", "1970-11-01", "1975-03-01", "1980-07-01", "1982-11-01", "1991-03-01", "2001-11-01", "2009-06-01") 
  ) %>%
  mutate(From = ymd(from), 
         To=ymd(to),
         duration_days = To-From)


yield_curve_recessions <- yield_curve %>%
  select(date, price, var) %>%
  filter(var %in% c("3-Month Treasury Bill", "10-Year Treasury Rate")) %>%
  spread(var, price) %>%
  rename_with(~ tolower(gsub("-", "", .x, fixed = TRUE))) %>%
  rename_with(~ tolower(gsub("10", "ten", .x, fixed = TRUE))) %>%
  rename_with(~ tolower(gsub("3", "three", .x, fixed = TRUE))) %>%
  rename_with(~ tolower(gsub(" ", "_", .x, fixed = TRUE))) %>%
  mutate(spread = tenyear_treasury_rate - threemonth_treasury_bill)

5 Challenge 2:GDP components over time and among countries

At the risk of oversimplifying things, the main components of gross domestic product, GDP are personal consumption (C), business investment (I), government spending (G) and net exports (exports - imports).

The GDP data we will look at is from the United Nations National Accounts Main Aggregates Database, which contains estimates of total GDP and its components for all countries from 1970 to today. We will look at how GDP and its components have changed over time, and compare different countries and how much each component contributes to that countrys GDP. The file we will work with is GDP and its breakdown at constant 2010 prices in US Dollars and it has already been saved in the Data directory. Have a look at the Excel file to see how it is structured and organised.

# load the data
UN_GDP_data  <-  read_excel(here::here("data", "Download-GDPconstant-USD-countries.xls"),
sheet="Download-GDPconstant-USD-countr",
skip=2)

The first thing you need to do is to tidy the data, as it is in wide format and you must make it into long, tidy format. Please express all figures in billions (divide values by 1e9, or \(10^9\)), and you want to rename the indicators into something shorter.

tidy_GDP_data  <-  UN_GDP_data %>%
  pivot_longer(cols = 4:51, names_to = 'Year', values_to = 'Value') %>% 
  filter(IndicatorName %in% c('Gross capital formation',
'Exports of goods and services',
'Imports of goods and services',
'General government final consumption expenditure',
'Household consumption expenditure (including Non-profit institutions serving households)',
'Gross Domestic Product (GDP)')) %>%
  mutate(Value = Value/1e9) %>% 
  
   # rename indicators using case_when and mutate
  mutate(IndicatorName = case_when(IndicatorName == 'Gross capital formation' ~ 'Gross capital formation',
  IndicatorName == 'Exports of goods and services' ~ 'Exports',
  IndicatorName == 'Imports of goods and services' ~ 'Imports',
  IndicatorName == 'General government final consumption expenditure' ~ 'Government expenditure',
  IndicatorName == 'Household consumption expenditure (including Non-profit institutions serving households)' ~ 'Household expenditure',
  IndicatorName == 'Gross Domestic Product (GDP)' ~ 'GDP_given'))

Even though there is an indicator Gross Domestic Product (GDP) in your dataframe, I would like you to calculate it given its components discussed above.

What is the % difference between what you calculated as GDP and the GDP figure included in the dataframe?

# Here,I first arrange the data into wide format and thus this would be much easier to read and analyze
tidy_GDP_data_calculation  <-  UN_GDP_data %>%      
  pivot_longer(cols = 4:51, names_to = 'Year', values_to = 'Value') %>%  
  filter(IndicatorName %in% c('Gross capital formation',
'Exports of goods and services',
'Imports of goods and services',
'General government final consumption expenditure',
'Household consumption expenditure (including Non-profit institutions serving households)',
'Gross Domestic Product (GDP)')) %>%
  mutate(Value = Value/1e9) %>% 
  
  # rename indicators using case_when and mutate
  mutate(IndicatorName = case_when(IndicatorName == 'Gross capital formation' ~ 'I',
  IndicatorName == 'Exports of goods and services' ~ 'X',
  IndicatorName == 'Imports of goods and services' ~ 'IM',
  IndicatorName == 'General government final consumption expenditure' ~ 'G',
  IndicatorName == 'Household consumption expenditure (including Non-profit institutions serving households)' ~ 'C',
  IndicatorName == 'Gross Domestic Product (GDP)' ~ 'GDP_given'))%>%
 
  # Arrange the data in wide format
   pivot_wider(names_from='IndicatorName',values_from='Value') %>%

# Calculate the variable using formula
   mutate(calculated_GDP = C+I+G+X-IM,na.rm=FALSE)%>%

# Calculate the difference
   mutate(percent_difference=(GDP_given-calculated_GDP)/GDP_given) 

skim(tidy_GDP_data_calculation$percent_difference)

Replicate the plot

tidy_GDP_data_plot2  <-  UN_GDP_data %>%
  pivot_longer(cols = 4:51, names_to = 'Year', values_to = 'Value') %>% 
  filter(IndicatorName %in% c('Gross capital formation',
    'Exports of goods and services',
    'Imports of goods and services',
    'General government final consumption expenditure',
    'Household consumption expenditure (including Non-profit institutions serving households)',
    'Gross Domestic Product (GDP)')) %>%
  mutate(Value = Value/1e9) %>% 
  
  # rename indicators using case_when and mutate
  mutate(IndicatorName = case_when(IndicatorName == 'Gross capital formation' ~ 'I',
  IndicatorName == 'Exports of goods and services' ~ 'X',
  IndicatorName == 'Imports of goods and services' ~ 'IM',
  IndicatorName == 'General government final consumption expenditure' ~ 'G',
  IndicatorName == 'Household consumption expenditure (including Non-profit institutions serving households)' ~ 'C',
  IndicatorName == 'Gross Domestic Product (GDP)' ~ 'GDP_given')) %>%
  
  # Arrange the data in wide format
   pivot_wider(names_from='IndicatorName',values_from='Value') %>%
  
  # Create a variable called Net Exports 
   mutate(NX=X-IM) %>%
  
  # Calculate proportion
   mutate('Government Expenditure'=G/GDP_given,'Gross capital formation'=I/GDP_given,
          'Household Expenditure'=C/GDP_given,'Net Exports'=NX/GDP_given) %>%
  
   select(1:3,9:14) %>%
  
  # Make the data into long format again
  pivot_longer(cols='Government Expenditure':'Net Exports',names_to='IndicatorName',values_to='proportions')
 
# Let us compare GDP components for these 3 countries
country_list <- c("United States","India", "Germany")

tidy_GDP_data_plot2 %>%
  
  # filter for country and indicator
  filter(Country %in% country_list) %>% 
  
  # order indicators s.t they are in the same order as in the plot
  mutate(IndicatorName = factor(IndicatorName, levels = c('Government Expenditure',
                                                          'Gross capital formation',
                                                          'Household Expenditure',
                                                          'Net Exports'))) %>% 
  # Code for the plot
  ggplot() +
  geom_line(aes(x = Year, y = proportions, group = IndicatorName, color = IndicatorName), size = 0.8) +
  
  #adjust the scale
  scale_x_discrete(breaks = c(1970,1980,1990,2000,2010)) +
  
  #adjust scale color
  scale_color_discrete(name = 'Components of GDP') +
  facet_wrap(~ Country) +
  labs(x = '',
       y = 'proportion',
       title = 'GDP and its breakdown at constant 2010 prices in US Dollars',
       caption = 'Source:United Nations,https://unstats.un.org/unsd/snamma/Downloads')  + 
  
  #adjust decimal place on y-axis 
  scale_y_continuous(labels=label_percent(accuracy=0.1))+
  
  theme_bw()

What is this last chart telling you? Can you explain in a couple of paragraphs the different dynamic among these three countries?

From the aspect of time series for each country solely, we found that Germany was rather steady in household expenditure and government expenditure throughout the last fifty years, while the country experienced a long and shacky decrease in gross capital formation index and an obvious upward slope in the net export sector since the year of 2000. Indias gross capital formation and net export were both quite stable except that around the year 2010 its net export experienced a huge drop but recovered very soon. The countrys household expenditure has been dropping, dramatically, during the last fifty years while its gross capital formation started to grow sharply at the year 2000. The index mentioned above were relatively steady for the USA. The household expenditure has been growing steadily over the period for an overall 10% increase. The government expenditure dropped roughly 10% for the last fifty years. The gross capital expenditure and net export had its up and downs with a range no more than 5% change. We take these three countries into comparison and found that India was the only country who built up the gross capital formation over the past fifty years. The country chose to invest rather than consume since it is still a developing country.And Germany was the only country managed to generate profit from trading in the last twenty years.

# Let us compare China's GDP components with the other two countries
country_list <- c("United States","China", "Germany")

tidy_GDP_data_plot2 %>%
  
  # filter for country and indicator
  filter(Country %in% country_list) %>% 
  
  # order indicators s.t they are in the same order as in the plot
   mutate(IndicatorName = factor(IndicatorName, levels = c('Government Expenditure',
                                                          'Gross capital formation',
                                                          'Household Expenditure',
                                                          'Net Exports'))) %>%
  
  ggplot() +
  geom_line(aes(x = Year, y = proportions, group = IndicatorName, color = IndicatorName), size = 0.8) +

       y = 'proportion',
       title = 'GDP and its breakdown at constant 2010 prices in US Dollars',labels=c("Government Expenditure","Gross Capital Formation","Household Expenditure","Net Exports"),
       caption = 'Source:United Nations,https://unstats.un.org/unsd/snamma/Downloads') +
  
  #adjust decimal place on y-axis 
  scale_y_continuous(labels=label_percent(accuracy=0.1))+
  theme_bw()

Based on the data of my country, which is also a developing country, it invests a lot on gross capital formation and the proportion keeps increasing until 2010. That is probably due to the spending on infrastructures. We are able to see how fast-changing China is in the recent thirty years. The interesting finding is the household expenditure component keeps decreasing til 2010. This might due to the reason that Chinese household prefer saving their money into the bank to consuming.
